<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Choose by Elevation and Distance from Pacific</strong> - Sonoma's diverse microclimates create dramatically different wine styles within short distances. Higher elevation vineyards like those on Sonoma Mountain (1,000+ feet) produce more structured, mineral-driven wines with higher acidity, while valley floor sites near Petaluma Gap experience strong marine influence, creating wines with bright acidity and herbal notes. Look for AVA designations like Bennett Valley for elegant Pinot Noir or Alexander Valley for bold Cabernet Sauvignon.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Russian River Pinot Noir at 58-60°F</strong> - Sonoma's cool-climate Pinot Noirs from Russian River Valley and Sonoma Coast benefit from slightly warmer serving temperatures than Burgundy due to their higher alcohol content (typically 14-15% ABV) and riper fruit character. This temperature allows the wine's signature cherry and strawberry flavors to shine while maintaining the region's characteristic earthy undertones from Goldridge soils.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Dry Creek Zinfandel for 30 Minutes Maximum</strong> - Old-vine Zinfandels from Dry Creek Valley's well-draining soils are naturally high in tannins but also volatile compounds. Brief decanting (20-30 minutes) helps integrate the wine's bold blackberry and spice flavors while preventing over-oxidation that can mute Zinfandel's signature jammy character. Skip decanting entirely for wines over 15 years old.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Sonoma Coast Chardonnay</strong> - The mineral-driven, restrained style of Sonoma Coast Chardonnay—shaped by cool marine fog and Franciscan shale soils—performs best in smaller-bowled Burgundy glasses rather than large Chardonnay glasses. This concentrates the wine's subtle citrus and wet stone aromas while preventing the delicate fruit from becoming diffuse.</li>

  <li><strong>Age Alexander Valley Cabernet 8-12 Years for Optimal Drinking</strong> - The warm, well-drained volcanic soils of Alexander Valley produce Cabernet Sauvignon with generous fruit and firm tannins that require proper aging. Most premium bottlings hit their stride at 8-12 years when the blackcurrant fruit integrates with cedar and tobacco notes from American and French oak. The region's consistent weather patterns create wines with excellent aging potential of 15-20 years.</li>

  <li><strong>Drink Sonoma County Rosé Within 18 Months</strong> - Sonoma's rosé production, primarily from Pinot Noir and Grenache grapes, benefits from the region's extended growing season and diurnal temperature variation. However, these wines are crafted for immediate consumption to showcase their bright watermelon and white peach flavors. The natural acidity from cool morning fog preserves freshness, but drink within 18 months to avoid losing the wine's vibrant character.</li>

  <li><strong>Pair with Local Ingredients to Maximize Terroir Expression</strong> - Sonoma wines are specifically crafted to complement the region's agricultural abundance. The herbaceous notes in Sonoma Sauvignon Blanc from marine-influenced sites pair perfectly with local goat cheese, while the earthy undertones in Russian River Pinot Noir complement wild mushrooms and salmon—foods that thrive in the same cool, foggy climate that shapes these wines.</li>

  <li><strong>Buy Sonoma Vintages Based on Rainfall Patterns</strong> - Unlike other California regions, Sonoma's proximity to the Pacific makes vintage variation significant. Drought years (2012-2016) produced concentrated, powerful wines ideal for aging, while balanced rainfall years like 2018 and 2019 created elegant wines perfect for earlier consumption. Excessive rain years like 2017 required careful producer selection, with hillside vineyards generally outperforming valley floor sites.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Sonoma's diverse terroir produces wines with varying aging potential, from immediate-drinking Pinot Noirs to age-worthy Cabernet Sauvignons that develop magnificently over decades.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Premium Cabernet Sauvignon</strong> (Alexander Valley, Knights Valley): 15-25 years peak aging</li>
<li><strong>Russian River Pinot Noir</strong>: 8-12 years for top producers like Williams Selyem</li>
<li><strong>Dry Creek Zinfandel</strong>: 10-15 years for concentrated, well-structured examples</li>
<li><strong>Sonoma Coast Chardonnay</strong>: 5-10 years for mineral-driven, age-worthy styles</li>
</ul>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Sonoma Cabernet Sauvignon transforms dramatically during cellaring. Young wines display intense cassis and eucalyptus notes with firm tannins. After 5-7 years, secondary flavors emerge—leather, tobacco, and cedar from oak integration. Peak maturity brings tertiary complexity: forest floor, graphite, and integrated fruit with silky tannins.</p>

<p>Russian River Pinot Noir evolves from bright cherry and cola to earthy mushroom and truffle notes, while maintaining its signature silky texture. The region's cool climate preserves acidity essential for graceful aging.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
<div class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
<ul>
<li><strong>Temperature</strong>: 55-58°F consistent (Sonoma's temperature swings make controlled storage crucial)</li>
<li><strong>Humidity</strong>: 60-70% to prevent cork drying</li>
<li><strong>Position</strong>: Bottles horizontal for cork contact</li>
<li><strong>Light</strong>: Complete darkness to prevent UV degradation</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>
<p><strong>Proper aging</strong> shows clear wine with sediment formation, evolved aromatics, and balanced acidity. <strong>Spoilage signs</strong> include cloudy appearance, vinegar-like aromas, or excessive oxidation (sherry-like notes in red wines). Sonoma's high-quality corks typically maintain integrity for 15+ years when properly stored, though vintage variation affects longevity—exceptional years like 2013 and 2016 show extended aging potential.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Sonoma and Napa Valley wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma wines tend to be more diverse and food-friendly due to the region's varied microclimates and proximity to the Pacific Ocean, while Napa focuses heavily on Cabernet Sauvignon. Sonoma produces exceptional Pinot Noir, Chardonnay, and Zinfandel across multiple AVAs, often at more accessible price points than Napa. The cooler coastal influence in areas like Russian River Valley creates wines with higher acidity and more elegant profiles compared to Napa's warmer, more concentrated styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
