  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are Sonoma wines good for beginners or too complex?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma wines are excellent for beginners because they typically have better natural acidity and food-pairing versatility than many California regions. Dry Creek Valley Sauvignon Blanc and Russian River Valley Pinot Noir are particularly approachable, with bright fruit flavors and moderate alcohol levels. The region's diverse styles mean you can explore everything from crisp whites to full-bodied reds without the intimidation factor of ultra-premium pricing found elsewhere in California.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value in Sonoma wine under $30?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma County appellation wines (not sub-AVA specific) often deliver exceptional value, with producers like Benziger, Cline, and Kunde offering quality Zinfandel and Chardonnay for $15-25. Look for Dry Creek Valley Zinfandel from smaller producers like Peterson or Papapietro Perry's second labels. These wines capture Sonoma's terroir character without the premium pricing of specific vineyard designations, making them perfect for everyday drinking.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I age Sonoma wines or drink them young?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Sonoma wines are designed to be approachable young but can age beautifully for 5-15 years depending on the style. Russian River Pinot Noir typically peaks at 3-7 years, while Alexander Valley Cabernet can develop for 10-15 years. Sonoma's natural acidity and moderate alcohol levels actually make these wines more age-worthy than many assume, but they're equally enjoyable upon release thanks to the region's balanced growing conditions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Sonoma wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is assuming all Sonoma wines are the same style—the region encompasses 18 different AVAs with dramatically different climates and soil types. Buying a Sonoma Coast Pinot Noir expecting the richness of an Alexander Valley Cabernet will lead to disappointment. Always pay attention to the specific AVA designation on the label, as this tells you far more about the wine's character than just seeing "Sonoma County" on the bottle.</p>
  </div>

